100–Deceased","1190":"1190","1205":"1205","1204":"1204","1147":"1147","1145":"1145","1100":"1100","1110":"1110","1174":"1174","1170":"1170","Frampton, Lincolnshire, England":"Frampton, Lincolnshire, England","Warkworth, Northumberland, England":"Warkworth, Northumberland, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Lyons","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: variant of   Lyon   3.","Irish: adopted for <b>Ó Laighin</b> (see   Lyne  ,   Lane  ,   Lyon  ) or <b>Ó Liatháin</b> (see   Lehane  )."],"variants":[{"name":"Lions","meanings":["English: variant of   Lyons  ."]},{"name":"Lyon","meanings":["Scottish, English, and French: from the personal name Middle English <i>Lyon</i>, Old French <i>Leon</i> (from Latin <i>leo</i> ‘lion’, or the cognate Greek <i>leōn</i>; see   Leon  ). Compare   Lyall  .","Scottish and English (of Norman origin): habitational name from Lyons-la-Forêt in Eure, Normandy. It is unlikely to be from the better-known southern French city of Lyon (see 5 below).","English and French: nickname from Middle English <i>lioun</i> ‘lion’ (Old English, Latin <i>leo</i>), Old French <i>leon</i>, perhaps applied to a brave, fierce, or proud person, or one with a shaggy mane of hair. Compare   Lion  ."]}]},{"name":"John","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["As a boy's name this represents a revival of Middle English <i>Jan</i>, a by‐form of   John  , or an adoption of the common European form with this spelling. As a girl's name it is a short form of names such as   Janet   and   Janice ."],"variants":[]},{"name":"ll","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Short form of any of the names beginning with this syllable."],"variants":[{"name":"Alexander","meanings":["From the Latin form of the Greek name <i>Alexandros</i>, from <i>alexein</i> ‘to defend’ + <i>anēr</i> ‘man, warrior’ (genitive <i>andros</i>). The name became extremely popular in the post-classical period, and was borne by several individuals in the New Testament and some early Christian saints. Its use as a common given name throughout Europe, however, derives largely from the fame of  Alexander the Great , King of Macedon (  356–323  bc  ), around whom a large body of popular legend grew up in late antiquity, much of which came to be embodied in the medieval ‘Alexander romances’."]},{"name":"Alan","meanings":["Of Celtic origin and uncertain derivation (possibly a diminutive of a word meaning ‘rock’). It was introduced into England by  Breton  followers of  William the Conqueror , most notably  Alan , Earl of Brittany, who was rewarded for his services with vast estates in the newly conquered kingdom. In Britain the variants  <b>Allan</b>  and  <b>Allen</b>  are considerably less frequent, and generally represent transferred uses of surname forms, whereas in America all three forms of the name are approximately equally common.  See also  Alun ."]},{"name":"Albert","meanings":["From an Old French name, <i>Albert</i>, of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>adal</i> ‘noble’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’. This was adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to England, displacing the Old English form <i>Æþelbeorht</i>. The name is popular in a variety of forms in Western Europe, and has been traditional in a number of European princely families. It was out of favour in England for centuries, however, and the revival of its popularity in the 19th century was largely in honour of  Queen Victoria's  consort,  Prince Albert of Saxe-Coburg-Gotha ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When John ll de Lyons was born in 1145, in Warkworth, Northumberland, England, his father, John de Lyons, was 36 and his mother, Elizabeth de Warkworth, was 45. He married Elizabeth de Warkworth in 1170, in Warkworth, Northumberland, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 son. He died in 1204, in Frampton, Lincolnshire, England, at the age of 59, and was buried in Frampton, Lincolnshire, England."},"et":{"1145–1204":"1145–1204","1145–1190":"1145–1190","1147–1174":"1147–1174","1174–1205":"1174–1205","1110–Male":"1110–Surnud","1100–Female":"1100–Surnud","1190":"1190","1205":"1205","1204":"1204","1147":"1147","1145":"1145","1100":"1100","1110":"1110","1174":"1174","1170":"1170","Frampton, Lincolnshire, England":"Frampton, Lincolnshire, England","Warkworth, Northumberland, England":"Warkworth, Northumberland, England"},"fi":{"1145–1204":"1145–1204","1145–1190":"1145–1190","1147–1174":"1147–1174","1174–1205":"1174–1205","1110–Male":"1110–Kuollut","1100–Female":"1100–Kuollut","1190":"1190","1205":"1205","1204":"1204","1147":"1147","1145":"1145","1100":"1100","1110":"1110","1174":"1174","1170":"1170","Frampton, Lincolnshire, England":"Frampton, Lincolnshire, England","Warkworth, Northumberland, England":"Warkworth, Northumberland, England"},"fr":{"1145–1204":"1145–1204","1145–1190":"1145–1190","1147–1174":"1147–1174","1174–1205":"1174–1205","1110–Male":"1110–Décédé","1100–Female":"1100–Décédée","1190":"1190","1205":"1205","1204":"1204","1147":"1147","1145":"1145","1100":"1100","1110":"1110","1174":"1174","1170":"1170","Frampton, Lincolnshire, England":"Frampton, Lincolnshire, Angleterre","Warkworth, Northumberland, England":"Warkworth, Northumberland, Angleterre","lifeSummary":"Lorsque John ll de Lyons est né en 1145, à Warkworth, Northumberland, Angleterre, son père, John de Lyons, avait 36 ans et sa mère, Elizabeth de Warkworth, avait 45 ans. Il a épousé Elizabeth de Warkworth en 1170, à Warkworth, Northumberland, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni. Ils ont eu au moins 1 fils. Il est décédé en 1204, à Frampton, Lincolnshire, Angleterre, à l’âge de 59 ans, et a été enterré à Frampton, Lincolnshire, Angleterre."},"de":{"1145–1204":"1145–1204","1145–1190":"1145–1190","1147–1174":"1147–1174","1174–1205":"1174–1205","1110–Male":"1110–Verstorben","1100–Female":"1100–Verstorben","1190":"1190","1205":"1205","1204":"1204","1147":"1147","1145":"1145","1100":"1100","1110":"1110","1174":"1174","1170":"1170","Frampton, Lincolnshire, England":"Frampton, Lincolnshire, England","Warkworth, Northumberland, England":"Warkworth, Northumberland, England","lifeSummary":"Als John ll de Lyons 1145 in Warkworth, Northumberland, England geboren wurde, war sein Vater John de Lyons 36 und seine Mutter Elizabeth de Warkworth 45. Er hat 1170 in Warkworth, Northumberland, England, United Kingdom Elizabeth de Warkworth geheiratet. Sie hatten mindestens 1 Sohn. Er starb 1204 im Alter von 59 Jahren in Frampton, Lincolnshire, England und wurde in Frampton, Lincolnshire, England begraben."},"ht":{"1145–1204":"1145–1204","1145–1190":"1145–1190","1147–1174":"1147–1174","1174–1205":"1174–1205","1110–Male":"1110–Desede","1100–Female":"1100–Desede","1190":"1190","1205":"1205","1204":"1204","1147":"1147","1145":"1145","1100":"1100","1110":"1110","1174":"1174","1170":"1170","Frampton, Lincolnshire, England":"Frampton, Lincolnshire, England","Warkworth, Northumberland, England":"Warkworth, Northumberland, England"},"hu":{"1145–1204":"1145–1204","1145–1190":"1145–1190","1147–1174":"1147–1174","1174–1205":"1174–1205","1110–Male":"1110–elhunyt